The U.S. specialty steel industryand its union said they will seek a three-year extension ofPresident Reagan's import restraint program to give theindustry more time to restore competitiveness.    They said they will tell the U.S. International TradeCommission (ITC) Thursday that "termination will have disastrousconsequences for American companies and workers."    The current four-year voluntary program reached withforeign exporters ends this summer and the ITC must advisePresident Reagan on the economic effect of its termination.    The Specialty Steel Industry of the United States and theUnited Steelworkers Union said in statement that imported steelwas still flooding the domestic market and continued curbs wereneeded to restore the industry's health.    Reagan is to decide by July 19 whether to renew therestraint program. Reuter&#3;